Here's an example of a Java code that demonstrates how a computer system can improve workflow efficiency in the finance industry:
```
import java.util.Scanner;
public class LoanCalculator {
 public static void main(String[] args) {
 Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
 System.out.print("Enter loan amount: ");
 double loanAmount = input.nextDouble();
 System.out.print("Enter interest rate: ");
 double interestRate = input.nextDouble();
 System.out.print("Enter loan term (in years): ");
 int loanTerm = input.nextInt();
 double monthlyInterestRate = interestRate / 1200;
 int numberOfPayments = loanTerm * 12;
 double monthlyPayment = (loanAmount * monthlyInterestRate) / (1 - Math.pow(1 + monthlyInterestRate, -numberOfPayments));
 System.out.printf("Monthly payment: $%.2f", monthlyPayment);
 }
}
```
This code is a simple loan calculator that takes in user input for the loan amount, interest rate, and loan term, and calculates the monthly payment using the formula for a loan payment. By using this code, financial institutions can automate the loan calculation process and reduce the time and effort required to calculate loan payments manually. This can help to improve workflow efficiency and allow financial institutions to process loan applications faster.

Yes, I can help you with that. Here is an example function that takes an HTML document as input, counts the number of words in each paragraph, and displays the results in a table format:
```javascript
function countWordsInParagraphs(html) {
 // create a temporary element to parse the HTML
 var temp = document.createElement('div');
 temp.innerHTML = html;

 // get all the paragraphs in the HTML
 var paragraphs = temp.getElementsByTagName('p');

 // create a table to display the results
 var table = document.createElement('table');
 var headerRow = table.insertRow();
 var paragraphHeader = headerRow.insertCell();
 paragraphHeader.innerHTML = 'Paragraph';
 var wordCountHeader = headerRow.insertCell();
 wordCountHeader.innerHTML = 'Word Count';

 // loop through each paragraph and count the number of words
 for (var i = 0; i < paragraphs.length; i++) {
 var paragraph = paragraphs[i];
 var words = paragraph.innerText.split(' ');
 var wordCount = words.length;

 // create a row in the table for each paragraph
 var row = table.insertRow();
 var paragraphCell = row.insertCell();
 paragraphCell.innerHTML = 'Paragraph ' + (i + 1);
 var wordCountCell = row.insertCell();
 wordCountCell.innerHTML = wordCount;
 }

 // append the table to the document
 document.body.appendChild(table);
}
```
To use this function, simply call it with the HTML document as a string:
```javascript
var html = 'This is the first paragraph.

This is the second paragraph.

';
countWordsInParagraphs(html);
```
This will display a table with two rows, one for each paragraph, showing the number of words in each paragraph.

