Here's an example Java code that uses regular expressions to extract and display the dates and locations of historical events mentioned in the text of the First Amendment:
```
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;
public class FirstAmendment {
 public static void main(String[] args) {
 String text = "Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion,or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech,or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble,and to petition the Government for a redress of grievances.";
 Pattern datePattern = Pattern.compile("bd{4}b"); // matches any four-digit number
 Pattern locationPattern = Pattern.compile("(?i)b[A-Z]{1}[a-z]+[s-][A-Z]{1}[a-z]+b"); // matches any capitalized word followed by a space or hyphen and another capitalized word
 Matcher dateMatcher = datePattern.matcher(text);
 Matcher locationMatcher = locationPattern.matcher(text);
 System.out.println("Historical Events Mentioned in the First Amendment:n");
 System.out.println("DatetLocation");
 while (dateMatcher.find() && locationMatcher.find()) {
 String date = dateMatcher.group();
 String location = locationMatcher.group();
 System.out.println(date + "t" + location);
 }
 }
}
```
This code uses two regular expressions: one to match any four-digit number (which we assume to be a date) and another to match any capitalized word followed by a space or hyphen and another capitalized word (which we assume to be a location).The code creates two Matcher objects,one for each regular expression,and uses them to find all matches in the text of the First Amendment.The code then prints out the results in a formatted table,with the date and location of each historical event on a separate line.

